me":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Aspall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Aspull in Greater Manchester, named from Old English <i>æspe</i> ‘aspen’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Asbell  .","Irish: in Ireland, this is usually the English name in 1 above imported, but according to MacLysaght it is also an east Leinster variant of   Archbold   (see   Archibald  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Asbell","meanings":["Altered form of English   Aspell  . Compare   Asbill  ,   Azbell  , and   Azbill  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":16,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":41,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Aspall was born in 1274, in Suffolk, England, his father, Richard de Aspall, was 11271 and his mother, Anne Coles, was 38. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth De Cressingham. He died in 1327, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1274–1327":"1274–1327","1285–1338":"1285–1338","1276–1339":"1276–1339","1294–1372":"1294–1372","1304–1357":"1304–1357","1308–1355":"1308–1355","1320–1372":"1320–1372","1237–1306":"1237–1306","about 1294":"umbes 1294","1274":"1274","1285":"1285","1372":"1372","1294":"1294","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1338":"1338","Abt 1273":"umbes 1273","1315":"1315","1304":"1304","1237":"1237","1357":"1357","1355":"1355","about 1304":"umbes 1304","1320":"1320","1276":"1276","before April 1306":"enne aprilli 1306","1308":"1308","after 15 April 1306":"pärast 15. aprilli 1306","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","1339":"1339","Lackford, Suffolk, England":"Lackford, Suffolk, England","Stonham Aspall, Suffolk, England":"Stonham Aspal, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Aspall, Suffolk, England":"Aspall, Suffolk, Eng